	(1,'Dance Workshop','2013-06-11-dance-workshop','2013-06-11 11:27:00','<p>Budding dancers in Whangarei got a special opportunity to learn from professionals at Whangarei Girls\' High School.\r\nMembers of the New Zealand Dance Company held two workshops at Girls\' High for 57 senior dance students ahead of their performance in town. Dance teacher Leone Neal said the opportunity was special for the girls.</p><p>\"They were really inspired. They took the students to a place that was\r\nmore creative than usual, and showed them it was okay to be really creative and original. They pushed them really hard,\" Ms Neal said.</p><p>The dancers held a performance at lunchtime that about 100 students attended. \"It was really funny and entertaining. I think a lot of them are looking forward to seeing them again on Saturday night. We don\'t get many dance companies coming to Whangarei,\" Ms Neal said.</p><p>The New Zealand Dance Company is on tour performing Language of Living at the Capitaine Bougainville Theatre, Forum North, tonight at 7.30pm, tickets from \"www.ticketek.co.nz\":http://www.ticketek.co.nz.</p>','<p>Budding dancers in Whangarei got a special opportunity to learn from professionals at Whangarei Girls&#8217; High School.<br />\nMembers of the New Zealand Dance Company held two workshops at Girls&#8217; High for 57 senior dance students ahead of their performance in town. Dance teacher Leone Neal said the opportunity was special for the girls.</p><p>&#8220;They were really inspired. They took the students to a place that was<br />\nmore creative than usual, and showed them it was okay to be really creative and original. They pushed them really hard,&#8221; Ms Neal said.</p><p>The dancers held a performance at lunchtime that about 100 students attended. &#8220;It was really funny and entertaining. I think a lot of them are looking forward to seeing them again on Saturday night. We don&#8217;t get many dance companies coming to Whangarei,&#8221; Ms Neal said.</p><p>The New Zealand Dance Company is on tour performing Language of Living at the Capitaine Bougainville Theatre, Forum North, tonight at 7.30pm, tickets from &#8220;www.ticketek.co.nz&#8221;:http://www.ticketek.co.nz.</p>','{\"excerpt\":{\"raw\":\"Members of the New Zealand Dance Company held two workshops at Girls\' High for 57 senior dance students ahead of their performance in town\",\"processed\":\"<p>Members of the New Zealand Dance Company held two workshops at Girls&#8217; High for 57 senior dance students ahead of their performance in town<\\/p>\"},\"image\":{\"_default\":\"\\/perch\\/resources\\/news\\/dance-12.jpg\",\"path\":\"dance-12.jpg\",\"size\":25295,\"bucket\":\"news\",\"w\":460,\"h\":271,\"sizes\":{\"thumb\":{\"w\":150,\"h\":88,\"path\":\"dance-12-thumb@2x.jpg\",\"size\":15910,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"},\"w375h320c1\":{\"w\":375,\"h\":220,\"density\":\"1\",\"path\":\"dance-12-w375h320.jpg\",\"size\":22070,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"},\"w75h50c1\":{\"w\":75,\"h\":50,\"density\":\"1\",\"path\":\"dance-12-w75h50.jpg\",\"size\":2540,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"},\"w150h100c1\":{\"w\":150,\"h\":100,\"density\":\"1\",\"path\":\"dance-12-w150h100.jpg\",\"size\":6376,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"},\"w180h120c1\":{\"w\":180,\"h\":120,\"density\":\"1\",\"path\":\"dance-12-w180h120.jpg\",\"size\":8182,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"},\"w200h150c1\":{\"w\":200,\"h\":150,\"density\":\"1\",\"path\":\"dance-12-w200h150.jpg\",\"size\":10016,\"mime\":\"image\\/jpeg\"}}}}','Dance','Published',1,0,NULL,NULL,0,'post.html'),
	(2,'Rachel Boyd - RSA Speech Winner','2013-04-04-rachel-boyd-rsa-speech-winner','2013-04-04 14:37:00','<p>Whangarei Girls\' High School student Rachel Boyd impressed the judges in Wellington on Wednesday with an emotive speech about Victoria Cross winner James Ward.</p><p>Miss Boyd, 18, spoke about how the men who served our country in the World Wars were around the same age as herself.</p><p>She highlighted Mr Ward\'s heroism and contrasted it with the new experiences people his age are going through around her.</p><p>\"These young men and women weren\'t deciding if their duvet spread matched their curtains, they were deciding whether or not to stand up and fight for New Zealand in a country miles away from home where life and death wasn\'t a sure thing each day,\" she said in her speech.</p><p>Mr Ward was a 22-year-old Wanganui school teacher when he fought for his\r\ncountry in WWII. </p><p>Rachel was one of eight Year 12 and 13 students from around the country to speak in the national final after winning her regional final.</p><p>The students had six to eight minutes to talk on the subject of \"New\r\nZealanders at War\". </p><p>RSA Chief Executive Stephen Clarke said the competition was a wonderful\r\ndemonstration of young Kiwis honouring the sacrifice and commitment made by so many before them.</p><p>\"Wartime must seem very distant to our young people today, but it\'s great\r\nto see that these students appreciate the courage and commitment of those who served for us,\" he said.</p><p>Miss Boyd was also awarded a $1000 travel fund, a trophy, a laptop and digital camera.</p>','<p>Whangarei Girls&#8217; High School student Rachel Boyd impressed the judges in Wellington on Wednesday with an emotive speech about Victoria Cross winner James Ward.</p><p>Miss Boyd, 18, spoke about how the men who served our country in the World Wars were around the same age as herself.</p><p>She highlighted Mr Ward&#8217;s heroism and contrasted it with the new experiences people 