	(179,8,'Content','/about-wghs/location/whangarei-northland.php','<h2>Whangarei</h2>\n\n<p>The largest city in Northland, Whangarei has a lively feel, but at the same time, remains a clean, safe environment with our friendly community ready to extend a warm welcome to all visitors.</p>\n\n<h3>Shopping</h3>\n\n<p>The Central Business District not only boasts the standard chain stores found in all cities, but also has a thriving quayside shopping district, where visitors can amble along Whangarei Harbour and enjoy the various museums, art galleries and cafes and bars as they go.  Whangarei has all the amenities of a large city, but without the big city bustle.</p>\n\n<h3>Beaches</h3>\n\n<p>Known for its natural beauty, Whangarei is host to many unspoilt beaches including Ocean Beach, Matapouri, Sandy Bay, Ruakaka to name a few.</p>\n\n<h3>Outdoor activities</h3>\n\n<p>The ‘Winterless North’, as it is known, has a community that enjoy the outdoors and with both beaches and nature on its doorstep, you will have an endless supply of outdoor activities to keep you occupied including; hiking, caving, abseiling, kayaking, camping, fishing, swimming and diving.</p>\n\n<h2>Northland</h2>\n\n<p><strong>Clean, Green, Safe - Northland is a land of unspoilt natural beauty</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>New Zealand’s warmest, subtropical climate</li>\n<li>Pristine beaches, bays and harbours</li>\n<li>Spectacular Forest</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Visit <a href=\"http://www.northlandnz.com\" title=\"Northland Tourism\">www.northlandnz.com</a> for more information on our unique home.</p>\n',0,2,'text_block.html',0,'{\"edit_mode\":\"singlepage\"}',1,2,2,'*'),
	(240,21,'Content','/about-wghs/sport.php','<h2>Hockey</h2>\n\n<p>A continuously strong code at Whangarei Girls’ High School, our students continue to excel in this sport.  2010 was no exception with Brooke Neal selected to attend the NZ Junior Hockey Academy while Rachael Lecky has received a National Leadership in Hockey Award.</p>\n\n<p>We have had numerous girls play NZ Hockey through the age groups which include past pupils; Charlotte Harrison, Alana Millington and Jacinda McLeod who all played for the New Zealand Women’s’ Black Sticks.</p>\n\n<p>In 2010 there were eight teams. Four play Women’s Grade and four play Collegiate Grade. The 1st XI plays in the Northland Hockey Association Premier Grade. They attend the National Secondary School’s championship and were the title holder in 2005.</p>\n\n<h2>Netball</h2>\n\n<p>In 2011 we have 19 teams playing the Whangarei Netball Association Saturday Competition.  Our top team plays in the Premier Grade and attends local, regional and the UNISS Netball Tournament annually.</p>\n\n<h2>Soccer</h2>\n\n<p>Whangarei Girls’ High School has three soccer teams this year.  The 1st XI plays in the Northland wide Mid Week Boys grade Secondary School Competition.  The team was promoted to the Premier League for 2009 NSS’s after winning the NSS Division Two Tournament last year.</p>\n\n<h2>Cricket</h2>\n\n<p>We have a strong 1st XI Cricket Team who took out the Leef Cup in a close final against Kamo High School in 2009.</p>\n\n<h2>Futsal</h2>\n\n<p>WGHS students Chelsey Webster, Nicola Anderson and Stacey Wright have all been selected for the NZ Vikings Futsal team.</p>\n\n<h2>Adventure Racing</h2>\n\n<p>Students wanting to participate in this sport can do so at a social and competitive level. Adventure Racing is an endurance sport that comprises of Orienteering, Problem Solving, Mountain Biking, Kayaking, Rock Climbing and everything in between. We go to a number of events throught the year, some local but mainly Auckland and Waikato based. Students race as individuals and in teams. Senior training starts at the beginning of the year and goes until May and Junior students start in June and go through till December. Overall we train as a large squad and form smaller teams based on the event.</p>\n',0,2,'text_block.html',0,'{\"edit_mode\":\"singlepage\"}',1,2,2,'*'),
	(22,11,'Content','/about-wghs/curriculum/index.php','<p>The vision in the new curriculum is for young people:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>who will be creative, energetic and enterprising</li>\n<li>who will seize the opportunities offered by new knowledge and technologies to secure a sustainable social, cultural, economic and environmental future for our country</li>\n<li>who will work to create an Aotearoa New Zealand in which Maori and Pakeha recognise each other as full treaty partners, and in which all cultures are valued for the contributions they bring</li>\n<li>who, in their school years, will continue to develop the values, knowledge and competencies that will enable them to live full and satisfying lives</li>\n<li>who will be confident, connected, actively involved and lifelong learners.”\nAs an important part of fulfilling this mission, and realising the vision, we are pleased to be able to offer you an extensive range of subjects.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Year 9 and 10</h2>\n\n<p>Year 9 and 10 students have a wide sampling from all the essential learning areas of the National Curriculum, and this gives each student a sound foundation for informed choices in the Senior School.</p>\n\n<p>All Year 9 students follow a compulsory programme in English, Mathematics, Science, Social Sciences, Health & Physical Education, Art and Technology. They also choose two option subjects. In Year 10 students follow a compulsory programme in English, Mathematics, Science, Social Sciences, Health & Physical education and select option subjects from a wide range of choices.</p>\n\n<h2>Yeah 11, 12 and 13</h2>\n\n<p>In Year 11 and 12, students choose 6 subjects for full year study and 5 subjects in Year 13. These courses lead to higher national qualifications at both academic and vocational levels.</p>\n',0,2,'text_block.html',0,'{\"edit_mode\":\"singlepage\"}',1,1,1,'*'),
	(239,21,'Intro text','/about-wghs/sport.php','\n<p class=\"intro-text\">Whangarei Girls\' High School is proud of the extensive range of sports on offer to all students.  We endeavour to cater for all student needs whether they be elite athletes striving to reach their full potential, social participants or students wanting to improve their fitness.</p>\n<hr />\n',0,1,'_intro_text.html',0,'[]',1,1,1,'*'),
	(46,23,'Content','/about-wghs/facilities.php','<p>WGHS is highly regarded for its attractive physical setting and well-resourced classrooms, particularly its: purpose-built (specialist) classrooms, hospitality suite (opened in 2006),impressive library(opened in 2000) and well-equipped science & technology suites. Enhancing student learning in an attractive environment is a key advantage at WGHS.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>6 computer labs, most with high power capability for design programmes.</li>\n<li>A space dedicated to International Students.</li>\n<li>Music Suite</li>\n<li>Well equipped Fideliter Centre with three gymnasiums including the brand new Manawahine Gym with it’s full size netball court.</li>\n<li>An all weather playing surface, climbing wall, swimming pool with diving boards, tennis courts.</li>\n<li>A large modern technology block.</li>\n<li>A modern well resourced Library.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A Performing Arts Centre for Drama and Dance is now in the planning stages and aiming to be ready for use beginning of 2012. This will enhance our already strong reputation for excellence in the Performing Arts.</p>\n',0,2,'text_block.html',0,'{\"edit_mode\":\"singlepage\"}',1,1,1,'*'),
	(251,30,'Intro text','/about-wghs/wghs-old-girls-association.php','\n<p class=\"intro-text\">The Whangarei Girls\' High School Old Girls\' Association 1 July 1948 to 2011</p>\n<hr />\n',0,1,'_intro_text.html',0,'[]',1,1,1,'*'),
	(60,30,'Content','/about-wghs/wghs-old-girls-association.php','<p>The first Annual General Meeting of the Assocation was held on 1 July 1948 with an attendance of 27 with Miss Dorothy Lupton as first President. The Constitution was read by Miss Lupton ‘clause by clause’ and Miss Bell was the first Patron, also the first Principal. She drew attention to the development of the school as a separate institution and its immediate needs. Money would be required for a swimming pool as well as additional tennis and basketball courts.</p>\n\n<p>The motto was to be ‘Fideliter’ and the school colours - blue, black and gold. These were adopted at this first meeting. We members of the Association look back with pride at the inspirations and devotion shown by these first Association members.</p>\n\n<p>One of the clauses in the Constitution states that the Association was formed for the promotion of cordial relations between members of the Association and present pupils of the school. This we have endeavoured to do over the yeras.</p>\n\n<p>We can look back with pride at the inspirations and loyalty shown to us by former Old Girls who have been our past Presidents and to the many Old Girls who have, through the years, served on our Committees from 1948 until 2011, when our AGM will be held in August. There will be many gaps - those who have left us- and we remember them. We have proudly kept our Association together through the 100 Year Centennial and 125 Year Jubilee celebrations.</p>\n\n<p>We continue to meet three time a year to decide how we can be of benefit to our school. Over the years we have given gifts to the school. These are mentioned in a yearly newsletter sent to Life Members. We take pride in the many achievements of pupils, past and present, in friendships, sports and academia. We applaud the many great teachers and principals who have, through the years, fulfilled the positions that have contributed to the achievements of young women of the school.</p>\n\n<p>Our Association can continue into the future to assist in any way we can to promote the ‘cordial relations’ that were instituted in our Constitution so many years ago.</p>\n\n<p>Footnote: “in later life, it can be said that there is far more to your school days than the mere acquisition of facts. You go for better and more lasting reasons - making friends, learning to be sociable and for maintaining individuality while being able to involve yourself with others and learning to accept success with modesty and defeat with goodwill”.</p>\n\n<p><em>Mrs Joyce Wilson (nee Hartnell) Life Member Whangarei Girls’ High School Old Girls’ Association</em></p>\n\n<h2>Apply for membership</h2>\n\n<p>Whangarei Girls’ High School Old Girls’s Association - <a href=\"/perch/resources/wghsoldgirlslifemembershipapplication.pdf\">WGHS Old Girls Life Membership Application</a> Application for Life Membership Life Membership Application</p>\n\n<h2>Past Principals</h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Miss Himmel - pre 1948</li>\n<li>Miss Littlejohn</li>\n<li>Miss Bell</li>\n<li>Miss Jones</li>\n<li>Miss Tombs</li>\n<li>Mr Bryant</li>\n<li>Mrs Joyce</li>\n<li>Mrs Sneddon</li>\n<li>Mrs Cooper</li>\n</ul>\n',0,2,'text_block.html',0,'{\"edit_mode\":\"singlepage\"}',1,4,4,'*'),
